1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,840
 So now we talked about cookies and how the server can set

2
00:00:03,840 --> 00:00:05,960
 cookies in the browser and how the browser has to give it back.

3
00:00:05,960 --> 00:00:09,880
 Now we're gonna actually do something useful with it, and that is we're going to build sessions.

4
00:00:09,880 --> 00:00:13,640
 And sessions is a place on the server where we record things like this user,

5
00:00:13,640 --> 00:00:15,760
 such and so of user has logged in.

6
00:00:15,760 --> 00:00:17,520
 So let's take a look at this.

7
00:00:17,520 --> 00:00:25,080
 So inside the server, there is some code that we've enabled in Django called session middleware.

8
00:00:25,080 --> 00:00:31,000
 And what it basically does is it kind of grabs every incoming request right before it comes in

9
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:36,940
 to urls.py and it sort of injects itself before urls.py runs.

10
00:00:36,940 --> 00:00:42,480
 And what it does is it uses the particular cookie value, maybe 3e, comes in as a cookie.

11
00:00:42,480 --> 00:00:47,240
 And then it actually grabs the particular session and associates it with our request.

12
00:00:47,240 --> 00:00:51,680
 And so by the time you're coming into one of your urls.py,

13
00:00:51,680 --> 00:00:56,200
 one of your views from urls.py, what you find is the cookies have all been set.

14
00:00:56,200 --> 00:00:57,880
 The session has been set up.

15
00:00:57,880 --> 00:01:00,440
 It's made a session if necessary.

16
00:01:00,440 --> 00:01:02,760
 It's looked up an old session if necessary.

17
00:01:02,760 --> 00:01:04,920
 And so there's a whole bunch of sessions.

18
00:01:04,920 --> 00:01:11,120
 And these sessions are stored in the database or on files or other kind of places.

19
00:01:11,120 --> 00:01:16,720
 And there is pretty much one session object for each distinct browser that's out there.

20
00:01:16,720 --> 00:01:21,160
 And we look them up by knowing what the cookie value was that we set it.

21
00:01:21,160 --> 00:01:23,560
 And so one of the things the session middleware does is,

22
00:01:23,560 --> 00:01:27,400
 if it doesn't see a cookie coming in, it actually like, well,

23
00:01:27,400 --> 00:01:30,880
 I'll pick a large random number and then I'll send the cookie back.

24
00:01:30,880 --> 00:01:34,240
 I will create a new session and I'll send the cookie back.

25
00:01:34,240 --> 00:01:38,440
 And then I'll be able to look that session up on all of the future requests.

26
00:01:38,440 --> 00:01:43,280
 So, usually we just go ahead and start sessions.

27
00:01:43,280 --> 00:01:45,000
 When we meet a new browser, it's simpler.

28
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:48,600
 I mean, you can sort of sometimes delay it to save a little bit of resources.

29
00:01:48,600 --> 00:01:53,240
 But often for most applications, right away you start using sessions and

30
00:01:53,240 --> 00:01:55,640
 then later you've logged a person in.

31
00:01:55,640 --> 00:01:58,840
 You are going to mark each browser with some unique random number.

32
00:01:58,840 --> 00:02:00,640
 And then when that cookie is sent back to us,

33
00:02:00,640 --> 00:02:04,840
 then we can re-associate the session with the incoming request.

34
00:02:04,840 --> 00:02:09,280
 So Django middleware handles the creation, deletion, the inserting of data,

35
00:02:09,280 --> 00:02:13,480
 the deleting of data, and the updating of data in these sessions.

36
00:02:13,480 --> 00:02:17,960
 The session identifier is a large random number that we put in a browser cookie.

37
00:02:17,960 --> 00:02:22,240
 The first time we meet a browser and then we store using that same number,

38
00:02:22,240 --> 00:02:23,480
 a bit of data on the server.

39
00:02:23,480 --> 00:02:27,800
 And then later when that cookie comes back in on an upcoming request,

40
00:02:27,800 --> 00:02:31,320
 we basically look up the session data and then re-associate it with the request

41
00:02:31,320 --> 00:02:35,440
 before we go through urls.py and into our views.

42
00:02:35,440 --> 00:02:42,480
 So we have to enable this and if you used Django admin to create your project,

43
00:02:42,480 --> 00:02:43,280
 this is already there.

44
00:02:43,280 --> 00:02:46,800
 You can go ahead and look in your settings.py and you'll see that it's there.

45
00:02:46,800 --> 00:02:51,240
 And you'll also notice that by now you've probably done a bunch of make migrations

46
00:02:51,240 --> 00:02:53,840
 and migrates and you see it making a session table.

47
00:02:53,840 --> 00:02:56,520
 So there's all kind of defaults that are set up so

48
00:02:56,520 --> 00:03:01,320
 that most of your first Django applications are set up to A, support sessions and

49
00:03:01,320 --> 00:03:03,000
 B, store sessions in the database.

50
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:07,520
 Which is a fine way to go for small to medium sized sites.

51
00:03:07,520 --> 00:03:09,800
 So like I said, they're gonna be stored in the database.

52
00:03:09,800 --> 00:03:14,240
 You do this migration and you see that it's creating a sessions table for you.

53
00:03:16,960 --> 00:03:20,200
 In your SQLite, db.sqlite3 database.

54
00:03:20,200 --> 00:03:23,560
 So here we go.

55
00:03:23,560 --> 00:03:26,600
 We have, as I said, out there, we've met these browsers.

56
00:03:26,600 --> 00:03:32,400
 We've made a session object in our database and we've put a cookie in each one.

57
00:03:32,400 --> 00:03:36,040
 So there's some kind of a cookie that they're all named the same.

58
00:03:36,040 --> 00:03:40,720
 So we'll name these cookies session ID or something.

59
00:03:40,720 --> 00:03:44,000
 And so what we've picked random numbers and we've marked them.

60
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:48,720
 And so what happens is, is that a browser, a browser comes in.

61
00:03:48,720 --> 00:03:53,800
 A browser sends a request in and they send their cookie along with it.

62
00:03:53,800 --> 00:03:57,240
 The Django middleware looks among all the sessions and

63
00:03:57,240 --> 00:04:00,120
 then connects it up and then it does the request.

64
00:04:00,120 --> 00:04:03,160
 So there's many browsers, each with a different number.

65
00:04:03,160 --> 00:04:05,800
 And then there's many sessions, each with a different number.

66
00:04:05,800 --> 00:04:09,720
 And part of reconnecting is creating it.

67
00:04:09,720 --> 00:04:14,480
 Now, if, if we look at this from the point of view of one browser and

68
00:04:14,480 --> 00:04:18,880
 one session object, one session storage area.

69
00:04:18,880 --> 00:04:23,800
 You know, at some point we come in and it, it re-associates the session and

70
00:04:23,800 --> 00:04:26,720
 we're doing some work and we're writing some stuff into the session.

71
00:04:26,720 --> 00:04:28,160
 And then we respond.

72
00:04:28,160 --> 00:04:30,000
 We go to another request.

73
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:31,680
 We can read what we wrote.

74
00:04:31,680 --> 00:04:35,040
 So we write stuff into the session, we can read it from another one.

75
00:04:35,040 --> 00:04:38,040
 And then here we can read that same information.

76
00:04:38,040 --> 00:04:39,960
 And then here we get a post.

77
00:04:39,960 --> 00:04:43,120
 We read a bunch of information, but we write some more information.

78
00:04:43,120 --> 00:04:48,000
 And so you can kind of think ultimately, just sort of at some level,

79
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:52,880
 relax about all the detail and realize that this session is a variable

80
00:04:52,880 --> 00:04:56,640
 that lasts across many request response cycles.

81
00:04:56,640 --> 00:05:02,720
 The, the cookie variable sort of also last across many request response cycles.

82
00:05:02,720 --> 00:05:04,880
 The get and the post data, they vanish.

83
00:05:04,880 --> 00:05:08,160
 So the get data for the, for each one.

84
00:05:08,160 --> 00:05:11,040
 You use it and you consume it or you store it in a database.

85
00:05:11,040 --> 00:05:15,160
 But the get data from one request is not available on the next request.

86
00:05:15,160 --> 00:05:19,560
 So we have to use things like sessions sometimes to store little bits of

87
00:05:19,560 --> 00:05:22,800
 information so that in a later request we can get it back.

88
00:05:22,800 --> 00:05:28,640
 So the, the request object has this little attribute called request session,

89
00:05:28,640 --> 00:05:30,080
 which is basically a dictionary.

90
00:05:30,080 --> 00:05:31,960
 We have, we can put keys in it.

91
00:05:31,960 --> 00:05:33,640
 We can delete those keys.

92
00:05:33,640 --> 00:05:35,040
 We can update those keys.

93
00:05:35,040 --> 00:05:39,320
 We can call .get and retrieve a key to see if it's there, etc., etc.

94
00:05:39,320 --> 00:05:42,880
 And so, in a sense, we just take request.session and

95
00:05:42,880 --> 00:05:44,480
 treat it as a magical dictionary.

96
00:05:44,480 --> 00:05:48,560
 Now, we have to remember that each browser has its own dictionary.

97
00:05:48,560 --> 00:05:53,480
 But when we're in a view function, we're only dealing with one browser.

98
00:05:53,480 --> 00:05:56,280
 And so that session is the one associated with that browser.

99
00:05:56,280 --> 00:05:59,080
 So it's a, it's this persistent interface,

100
00:05:59,080 --> 00:06:03,440
 persistent data that lasts across all these things.

101
00:06:03,440 --> 00:06:05,880
 So here's a real tiny view function.

102
00:06:05,880 --> 00:06:12,040
 And you can see in this view function what we're going to do is request.session.

103
00:06:12,040 --> 00:06:17,280
 This is where request.session is where you see the session data.

104
00:06:17,280 --> 00:06:18,440
 It's basically a dictionary.

105
00:06:18,440 --> 00:06:19,960
 So we can say .get.

106
00:06:19,960 --> 00:06:22,520
 Then we have a key and we have zero as the default.

107
00:06:22,520 --> 00:06:24,160
 Num visits is the key.

108
00:06:24,160 --> 00:06:25,720
 Zero is the default value.

109
00:06:25,720 --> 00:06:28,600
 And then we're going to get that and add one to it.

110
00:06:28,600 --> 00:06:30,280
 And then store that.

111
00:06:30,280 --> 00:06:33,280
 And this is kind of like how we do counting.

112
00:06:33,280 --> 00:06:37,960
 If we get it, if it was four before, we're going to go to plus one and get to five.

113
00:06:37,960 --> 00:06:42,920
 If it's not there, we just set it to zero, so we set it to one.

114
00:06:42,920 --> 00:06:48,560
 So somehow num visits is either one or one more than what was previously there.

115
00:06:48,560 --> 00:06:51,920
 And so then what we see is we see the line that actually just stores it back

116
00:06:51,920 --> 00:06:53,040
 into the session.

117
00:06:53,040 --> 00:06:55,880
 That's it, it's a dictionary, it's a magic dictionary.

118
00:06:55,880 --> 00:06:59,400
 It existed before it came in, and we're just going to leave it there.

119
00:06:59,400 --> 00:07:03,720
 And somehow magic things take care of updating all this stuff.

120
00:07:03,720 --> 00:07:07,360
 And so the other thing that we're going to do is we're going to have this go up by

121
00:07:07,360 --> 00:07:11,240
 one and if it gets over, we're going over four, then we're going to wipe it out.

122
00:07:11,240 --> 00:07:16,080
 So this will count one, two, three, four, one, two, three, four.

123
00:07:16,080 --> 00:07:20,160
 And well, actually, yeah, one, two, three, four, one, two, three, four.

124
00:07:20,160 --> 00:07:26,280
 And so this del is just the standard Python syntax to remove a entry from a,

125
00:07:26,280 --> 00:07:30,360
 to remove an entry from a dictionary.

126
00:07:30,360 --> 00:07:34,920
 And then we just kind of print out the number of visits in our little string and

127
00:07:34,920 --> 00:07:36,400
 our response.

128
00:07:36,400 --> 00:07:40,560
 And so if we go, we start, we have no cookie.

129
00:07:40,560 --> 00:07:43,080
 That means that we also then have no session.

130
00:07:43,080 --> 00:07:45,720
 And then we go into the session code, and

131
00:07:45,720 --> 00:07:48,760
 you see that it has set a session cookie, right?

132
00:07:48,760 --> 00:07:52,440
 So we see a session cookie called sesh ID.

133
00:07:52,440 --> 00:07:57,680
 That's got an expiration date, which is not a expire when the browser goes away

134
00:07:57,680 --> 00:08:00,320
 session, and it's got some big long random number.

135
00:08:00,320 --> 00:08:05,160
 And so that is basically the session ID until we get a new session.

136
00:08:05,160 --> 00:08:07,240
 And as a side effect of that,

137
00:08:07,240 --> 00:08:13,240
 we've also stored the value one inside the session in the server and printed it out.

138
00:08:13,240 --> 00:08:17,360
 So we went, we came in, we established a session.

139
00:08:17,360 --> 00:08:18,440
 We didn't do any of that, right?

140
00:08:18,440 --> 00:08:21,760
 If we look at our view here, we didn't establish the session.

141
00:08:21,760 --> 00:08:24,040
 All we did is grab something out of it, and

142
00:08:24,040 --> 00:08:27,360
 that's because the establishment of the session happens in the middleware that's

143
00:08:27,360 --> 00:08:29,040
 kind of outside of us.

144
00:08:29,040 --> 00:08:34,640
 And so the middleware happens before our code starts and after our code is done.

145
00:08:34,640 --> 00:08:38,160
 And so the session stuff is just taken care of when we do that.

146
00:08:38,160 --> 00:08:46,360
 So view count is one, and then what happens is when we just hit refresh,

147
00:08:46,360 --> 00:08:49,720
 it's going to send the cookie in for that session ID.

148
00:08:49,720 --> 00:08:54,760
 It's going to load up the session that's gj2233.

149
00:08:54,760 --> 00:08:57,040
 And then our code is going to add one to that number and

150
00:08:57,040 --> 00:08:59,840
 store it back into the session, and then it's going to be two.

151
00:08:59,840 --> 00:09:05,840
 And if we hit refresh, it would say three, four, then it would do a reset, we won.

152
00:09:05,840 --> 00:09:09,440
 And so in this code, we just kind of say request.session and

153
00:09:09,440 --> 00:09:12,200
 put stuff in it and read stuff out of it.

154
00:09:12,200 --> 00:09:16,200
 And the cookie is the thing that looks that up.

155
00:09:16,200 --> 00:09:19,720
 Now, if we wanted to take a look at what's in the session table,

156
00:09:19,720 --> 00:09:26,920
 it's really just a session and you can see that it gets created by your migrate and

157
00:09:26,920 --> 00:09:27,960
 your make migrations.

158
00:09:27,960 --> 00:09:31,520
 So we can go right into the database, we can ask for the tables.

159
00:09:31,520 --> 00:09:34,920
 We can see the django_session, and

160
00:09:34,920 --> 00:09:39,160
 then we can say select star from django_session.

161
00:09:39,160 --> 00:09:42,280
 And so that will show us the data that's there.

162
00:09:42,280 --> 00:09:47,800
 And so what we're gonna see is the key, which is that session key.

163
00:09:47,800 --> 00:09:50,760
 And then a time, and that's used to expire the session,

164
00:09:50,760 --> 00:09:53,360
 cuz these sessions don't last forever.

165
00:09:53,360 --> 00:09:56,680
 The Django middleware kind of cleans these up after a while.

166
00:09:56,680 --> 00:10:00,240
 Otherwise, you'd have sessions that just lasted forever and ever and ever.

167
00:10:00,240 --> 00:10:05,520
 And then the actual data is this big long string.

168
00:10:05,520 --> 00:10:08,680
 So what this is, is this is actually an encoded string.

169
00:10:08,680 --> 00:10:14,500
 And if you really wanna look at it, it's encoded using a technique called Base64.

170
00:10:14,500 --> 00:10:17,160
 And there's a Base64 parsing library.

171
00:10:17,160 --> 00:10:20,160
 Base64 is a way of taking arbitrary data and

172
00:10:20,160 --> 00:10:24,480
 encoding it in basically letters and numbers upper and lower case.

173
00:10:24,480 --> 00:10:26,640
 It's a little less dense.

174
00:10:26,640 --> 00:10:27,880
 I mean, it kind of expands.

175
00:10:27,880 --> 00:10:29,000
 It's not like a compression.

176
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:30,240
 It's the opposite of compression.

177
00:10:30,240 --> 00:10:37,920
 It expands it, but it expands the data when it's encoded into Base64.

178
00:10:37,920 --> 00:10:40,120
 But it also means that then you can store it.

179
00:10:40,120 --> 00:10:42,000
 You don't have to worry about any special characters.

180
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:44,600
 Cuz sometimes when you're going like pasting single quotes and

181
00:10:44,600 --> 00:10:46,880
 double quotes mess up, all that kind of stuff.

182
00:10:46,880 --> 00:10:50,160
 By saying here's this string, I'm gonna encode it in Base64,

183
00:10:50,160 --> 00:10:54,000
 I basically am guaranteed that there will be no weird,

184
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:57,600
 weird characters that will cause some kind of problem farther on down the line.

185
00:10:57,600 --> 00:11:05,280
 So if we take a look at our thing, and we grab the little thing,

186
00:11:05,280 --> 00:11:10,760
 that's the Base64 encoded variable, if you decode this,

187
00:11:10,760 --> 00:11:14,600
 we're gonna Base64 decode it, you see that ultimately it's just kind of like

188
00:11:14,600 --> 00:11:18,560
 a little key value pair that looks pretty much like a dictionary.

189
00:11:18,560 --> 00:11:21,000
 It's a serialized version of a dictionary.

190
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:25,560
 It's a dictionary that has been put into a serialized form.

191
00:11:25,560 --> 00:11:30,240
 And it's in also JSON format, and so we can actually sort of tear this apart and

192
00:11:30,240 --> 00:11:34,720
 use the JSON library to load it up and see what we've got.

193
00:11:34,720 --> 00:11:38,400
 So, so that's there, you don't have to worry too much about that.

194
00:11:38,400 --> 00:11:42,360
 It's just somehow this big long thing is being read and written and read and

195
00:11:42,360 --> 00:11:45,560
 written on every request response cycle.

196
00:11:45,560 --> 00:11:48,600
 That is certainly read on every request response cycle.

197
00:11:48,600 --> 00:11:51,920
 And it's written when you modify the data in the session.

198
00:11:51,920 --> 00:11:53,800
 So this has been a quick set of lectures.

199
00:11:53,800 --> 00:11:58,080
 We talked about cookies, a way of marking each browser with a big random number.

200
00:11:58,080 --> 00:12:02,200
 And then sessions, which are a bit of data that's stored in a database

201
00:12:02,200 --> 00:12:06,040
 indexed by that large random number, and then each request comes in,

202
00:12:06,040 --> 00:12:08,680
 we get the cookie back, and then we look up the session.

203
00:12:08,680 --> 00:12:11,880
 The data, session data, key values, key value pairs,

204
00:12:11,880 --> 00:12:14,440
 basically a dictionary, is all stored in there.

205
00:12:14,440 --> 00:12:20,160
 So we talked a little bit about how we do request.session in Django to implement,

206
00:12:20,160 --> 00:12:22,880
 to access session capabilities in our Django applications.

